As shown by a number of scribal notes, the manuscript was written in a female convent, most likely in a Dominican nunnery. This is suggested not only by internal content-related criteria, but especially by the fact that the first demonstrable owner was probably a Dominican nun at St. Catherine’s in Nuremberg, or alternatively at Maria Medingen

See the entry on fol. 1r:
“This book was commissioned to be written by the venerable in God, Lady Anna Gurr, abbess of the venerable convent at Neuburg, and it was completed on the feast of St Quirinus the holy martyr in the year of the Lord 1501, in the first year [of her abbacy].”

Anna Gurr († 1517) was abbess of the Benedictine convent of Neuburg an der Donau until 1509; see P. Lindner, Monasticon episcopatus Augustani antiqui, Bregenz 1913, p. 132 no. 180.
After the dissolution of their convent in 1554, the Neuburg nuns partly moved to Kühbach; thus the ownership note on fol. 1r is probably to be dated after 1554:
“This book belongs to Anna Rinckhamerin, nun of the convent at Kühbach.”

details.value: Watermark of a small bear with a short head and tiny ears, another bear with a longer snout on pages 87 and 89 , and another variant on page 90 with a wide-open snout and ears resembling a bump on the head. Precisely identifying the bear marks is difficult, as only parts are visible, and the paper is very thick.The empty pages 107 ff.have later watermarks: a large crown and at least one other watermark.Engler-Maurer , Rulebook (1998) identifies the bear WZ, without mentioning variants, withPiccard , watermark XV/2 (1987), section I, no. 287, without indication of place and date (recte: Tuttlingen, 1525).

details.value: 1. small ox head with eyes and nostrils, horizontally protruding ears, pole and star, similar to Piccard , watermark II/2 (1966), section VII, no. 126 (Basel, Frankfurt a. M., Cologne, 1454, 1455), and ibid. no. 338 (Bern, Breisach: 1450-1453);2. smaller ox head, f.17 , f.31 , with narrow nose and adjoining nostrils, without additional markings (or such cannot be found?), similar to Piccard , watermark II/2 (1966), section I, no. 211 (Radolfzell, Rottenburg a. N., 1459, 1460);3. Ox head, f.22 , with horizontally protruding, spoon-shaped (longish-round) ears and strikingly large nostrils (same size as the eyes), corresponding additional mark (pole with star?) not verifiable; similar to Piccard , watermark II/2 (1966), section VII, no. 282, more distantly similar also no. 286 (among others Basel, Konstanz, 1455-1457);4. f.165ff., f.255 , f.262 , f.264 , f.271 a mark that is difficult to define: two crossing, double-contoured rods, probably a pair of scissors, too little visible for precise identification;5. f.283f., f.274 Gothic P, only partially visible, do. f.284 , f.287 , f.290 ;6. f.331 and 314 fragments of a hip horn, never completely visible (always in the fold), do. f.429 , f.437 , until the end, traced in pencil on f.442v .

records.rec_Title: W 005 / Msc. VII (z.T. Dep.), Nr. 1319, Produced by Vinnenberg cloister, Cistercian, Warendorf, Germany, 1252-1465
Vinnenberg cloister, Cistercian, Warendorf, Germany, 1252-1465

details.value:
https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kloster_Vinnenberg
The first abbess mentioned in the chronicle was a certain Angela. She is said to have governed her monastery with "all reverence and spiritual zeal" and died in 1301. From this time onward, a continuous series of 28 abbesses is recorded in the chronicle.
Until the mid-15th century, the monastery was a Cistercian nunnery and subordinate to Marienfeld Abbey in Marienfeld . In the 15th century, the monastery experienced internal and external decline due to its integration into the economic and social structures of the time. Some of the nuns had become secularized, and a few possessed private property. In 1465, at the initiative of Bishop Johann of Münster and Abbot Heinrich von Kleve of Liesborn [ 8 ] , Abbess Ursula Swaneken succeeded in transforming the convent into a Benedictine abbey as part of a renewal of monastic life . From 1468 onward, it belonged to the Bursfeld Congregation and was placed under the authority of Liesborn Abbey .

records.rec_Title: Admont Stiftsbibliothek, Admont Ms.16, Produced by Admont Abbey, Benedictine, Admont, Austria, 1054
Admont Abbey, Benedictine, Admont, Austria, 1054

details.value: Abbot Wolfhold founded a convent for the education of girls of noble families; Gottfried of Venningen educated thirteen monks later chosen abbots of other monasteries. Abbot Henry VII (1275-97) began restoration work on the community, Engelbert (1297-1331)completed the restoration.

St. Hemma, Countess of Friesach and Zeltschach, founded community after entering convent at Gurk, leaving lands for the building of a monastery near the salt works of Hall. Foundation, however, was not begun until 1072, more than a quarter of a century after the Saint's death. Abbey church was consecrated by Gebhard von Helfenstein, Archbishop of Salzburg, in honour of St. Blasius in 1074. Gebhard also brought twelve monks from Salzburg to start community. In the following century, a school and community of women emerged from a less formal gathering of religious women around the parish church of S Amandus.
The associated nunnery ceased to exist during the Reformation.

Bamberg, Dominican convent of the Holy Sepulchre

The university library in Augsburg preserves two Breviaries from 1484 and 1486 respectively, owned by Adelheid Sparneck, #Oet.-Wall. II. 1.4o37/ Oett.-Wall. II. 1. 4o39/ and a life of S. Katherine of Alexandria from 1465/66, written by Martha Peurlin, Oett.-Wall. III. 1. 2o12/ a martyrology from the fifteenth century, Oett.-Wall. III. 1. 2o20/ a Vitas patrum from the fifteenth century, Oett.-Wall. III. 1. 2o25/ and Spiritual meditations, 1435, written by Joh. Liephart and owned by Martha Geringin, Oett.-Wall. III. 1. 4o5. The Staatsbibliothek in Bamberg preserves a Processionale, 1497, # HV Msc. 348 (Nro. 147) as well as # Bibl. 73, Williramus, In Cant. cant. 1523, written by A. Brunner, and # Lit. 71, 72, 92, 93, 105, 106, 107, 108, 109, 109d, 130, a Processionale, 1499, and # Theol. 65, Buch von der Gemahelschaft Christis, fifteenth century. The Landesbibliothek in Karlsruhe preserves several manuscripts from the community: # St. Georgen Pap. 8a/ St. Georgen Pap. 8b/ St. Peter Perg. 31a, Ritale, fifteenth century/ St. Peter Perg. 38, Berviary, c. 1500/ St. Peter Perg., 39/ St. peter Perg, 53a/ St. Peter Perg. 61/ St. Peter Perg. 64/ St. Peter Perg. 65/ St Peter Perg. 106/ and UH 11. Manuscript # Clm 28309 in the Staatsbibliothek in Munich may also come from this community. A Rituale from the fifteenth century is held in the German national museum in Nürnberg. In The Free Library in Philadelphia, # Lewis Eur. 161 (Phill. 1146), beginning "Super decr." from 1450 may also come from this community.

records.rec_Title:
Petersfrauen, Benedictine, Salzburg, Austria, 1113-
1583

details.value: Monastery of St Peter in Salzburg
(Their monastic brethren were known as the Petersherren.)

While knitting and needlework were also important activities, the Petersfrauen were especially known for their writing and illustration of Psalters and other liturgical manuscripts. The sisters also ran a school for young women, according to 15th century documentation (Schellhorn, Die Petersfrauen, 147).

- Ursula Satzenhofer, in the second half of the 15th century; translated the treatise “De passione Christi” of Silvester von Rebdorf (now found as Salzburg, St Peter, cod. B VIII 27). She came from the Regensburg convent of Niedermünster to join the Petersfrauen and professed on 9 August 1469. (2VL 8 col. 587).
- Wolfgang Walcher, the Petersfrauen confessor, translated a number of texts for the women in his care. Born in 1460 in Kösching bei Ingolstadt, Walcher had entered St Peter in Salzburg in 1479; became confessor to the Petersfrauen ca. 1490; and died 18 June 1518. (2VL 10, cols. 603-606 and Wolfgang Walchers Magdalenenlobgesang, here p. 245.)
- In winter 1511/1512 and again in 1523, Johann von Staupitz preached to the Petersfrauen. Modern editions of these sermons are available: Johann von Staupitz, Salzburger Predigten 1512 : eine textkritische Edition : philosophische Dissertation angenommen von der Neuphilologischen Fakultät der Universität Tübingen am 12. Juli 1984; Johann von Staupitz, Salzburger Predigten 1520, A mystic’s passion : the spirituality of Johannes von Staupitz in his 1520 Lenten sermons.
- Hans Wildsgeferd, a canon of Augsburg Cathedral (d. 1470) had arranged for books to be copied as a gift for "the religious sisters, prioress, and convent of the church of Saint Peter at Salzburg, so that they would pray to God for him." See The Life and Work of Clara Hätzlerin p. 4.


The women of the Petersfrauen were renowned scribes, creating documents for St. Peter’s use and accepting commissions from neighboring religious communities. The Psalters, breviaries, meditation books, prayer books and other manuscripts that they produced were often decorated with miniatures. The Petersfrauen Gradual (Salzburg, Stift St. Peter, a IX.11) from ca. 1190-1200 is available in facsimile. The lost psalter, prepared for Abbot Otto II Chalchosperger, was cited in the Registrum Ottonis f. 22v; he received the psalter from the Petersfrauen in 1404.

Fifteenth-century manuscripts copied by convent scribes include:
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St. Peter, cod. a II 7, a copy of the Passionstraktat of Johannes von Indersdorf and of Grunde aller Bosheit of Tauler, copied by Anna Ammanin and Erentrudis Schöttlin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. a II 17, Johannes dem Taufer, copied by Erentrudis Schöttlin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. a III 7, copied by Regina Mundtenheimerin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. a III 21, a 1448 copy of Petrus de Alliaco’s Geistliche Lieder, copied by Margarethe Hohenwarterin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. a III 28, texts of Hieronymus Posser copied by Katharina Pschachlin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. a IV 22, containing a copy of Thomas Peuntner’s Messerklarungen copied by Erentrudis Schöttlin and a meditation on the mass in prayer form copied by Katharina Pscachlin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. a VI 13, a copy of the Vocabularius ex quo and of Donatus copied by Katharina Pschachlin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St. Peter, cod. a VII 35, a miscellany containing Thomas a Kempis, Spruch from Vitas Patrum Albertus Magnus, sermons, and so on, dated 1455 and copied by Anna Ammanin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. b I 1, copied by Barbara (Katharina) Püchlerin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. b I 15, copied by Magdalena Halbergerin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St. Peter, cod. b I 24, a Lectionary which includes a prayer copied by Anna Ammanin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. b II 10, a volume of mystic/ascetic texts copied by Eufemia Reitterin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. b II 11, copied in 1523 by Dorothea Meixner.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. b III 8 a second volume of mystic/ascetic texts copied by Eufemia Reitterin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. b V 8, copied in 1520 by Dorothea Meixner.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St. Peter, cod. b V 40, a volume dated 1471 containing works by Tauler, Eckhart, Indersdorf, and Seuse, copied by Anna Ammanin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St. Peter, cod. b VI 12, works of Heinrich von Langenstein, copied by Anna Ammanin.
• Salzburg, Erzabtei St Peter, cod. b VIII 27, Silvester von Rebdorf’s Passionsbetrachtungen, etc., copied by Erentrudis Schöttlin.
• Salzburg Nonnberg cod. 23 D +29, Ps.-Augustinus, including the Manuale de verbo dei of Wolfgang Walcher, copied by Barbara (Katharina) Püchlerin and Dorothea Meixner.

Karlsruhe, Badische Landesbibliothek, Cod. Lichtenthal 105, Produced by Lichtenthal, Cistercian, Baden-Baden, Germany, 1245-
1789

Lichtenthal, Cistercian, Baden-Baden, Germany, 1 Jan 1245-
1789

details.value: Kloster unserer lieben Frau zu Lichtenthal; Lucida Vallis; Lucidevallis

The convent of Lichtenthal had an extensive library (see Manuscript sources). It possessed several Psalters, Breviaries, Graduals, Sermons, and lives of the saints. Several works were produced by a "Margaretha dicta Regula" during the course of the fifteenth century, including a Diurnal, Breviary, Solioquies of Bonaventura, Book of holy maids and women, Evangeliar., Leben der Altväter, Paradisus anime, The spiritual rosegarden, and Legend aurea.

Wolfenbüttel, Herzog August Bibliothek, Cod. Guelf. 204 Helmst., Produced by Lamspringe, Augustinian, Lamspringe, Lower Saxony, Germany, 845-1138

value.title: Wolfenbüttel, Herzog August Bibliothek, Cod. Guelf. 204 Helmst.
Lamspringe, Augustinian, Lamspringe, Lower Saxony, Germany, 845-1138

records.rec_Title: Lamspringe, Augustinian, Lamspringe, Lower Saxony, Germany, 845-1138

details.value: Lamspringe; sanctus Adrianus monasterium (873); ecclesia sancti Adriani lamesprinche (1149); ecclesia in Lamesprigge (1169); monasterium beatorum Adriani et Dyonisii martirum in Lammespringhe (1338)

The Herzog-August Bibliothek in Wolfenbüttel possesses 18 manuscript volumes, which belonged to the library of the convent. These are primarily theological and spiritual works, written from the tenth to the sixteenth century. Other documents are located in the HauptStaatsarchiv in Hannover.

A book from the convent (preserved in the Herzog-August-Bibliothek) mentions the nun Ermengarde (c. 1178/1205) as the scribe and as the painter of a miniature of S. Augustine. It is thus likely that the convent did possess a scriptorium (Römer, 370). There are 18 extant books from the convent, 12 stem from the twelfth century. Of the twelve, there are four works of Augustine, two of Gregory the Great, two from Venerable Bede, and one each by Hieronymus, Clemens, John Chrysostomos, and Hugo of S. Victor. Römer ascribes these works to the influence of provost Gerhard (1178-1205) (Römer, 335).

Augustinian canonesses; end of 12th century, changed to Benedictine convent
Augustinian; Benedictine by 1138

details.value:
https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kloster_Vinnenberg
The first abbess mentioned in the chronicle was a certain Angela. She is said to have governed her monastery with "all reverence and spiritual zeal" and died in 1301. From this time onward, a continuous series of 28 abbesses is recorded in the chronicle.
Until the mid-15th century, the monastery was a Cistercian nunnery and subordinate to Marienfeld Abbey in Marienfeld . In the 15th century, the monastery experienced internal and external decline due to its integration into the economic and social structures of the time. Some of the nuns had become secularized, and a few possessed private property. In 1465, at the initiative of Bishop Johann of Münster and Abbot Heinrich von Kleve of Liesborn [ 8 ] , Abbess Ursula Swaneken succeeded in transforming the convent into a Benedictine abbey as part of a renewal of monastic life . From 1468 onward, it belonged to the Bursfeld Congregation and was placed under the authority of Liesborn Abbey .

Lamspringe, Benedictine, Lamspringe, Lower Saxony, Germany,-1138

records.rec_Title: Lamspringe, Benedictine, Lamspringe, Lower Saxony, Germany,-1138

details.value: Lamspringe; sanctus Adrianus monasterium (873); ecclesia sancti Adriani lamesprinche (1149); ecclesia in Lamesprigge (1169); monasterium beatorum Adriani et Dyonisii martirum in Lammespringhe (1338)

The Herzog-August Bibliothek in Wolfenbüttel possesses 18 manuscript volumes, which belonged to the library of the convent. These are primarily theological and spiritual works, written from the tenth to the sixteenth century. Other documents are located in the HauptStaatsarchiv in Hannover.

A book from the convent (preserved in the Herzog-August-Bibliothek) mentions the nun Ermengarde (c. 1178/1205) as the scribe and as the painter of a miniature of S. Augustine. It is thus likely that the convent did possess a scriptorium (Römer, 370). There are 18 extant books from the convent, 12 stem from the twelfth century. Of the twelve, there are four works of Augustine, two of Gregory the Great, two from Venerable Bede, and one each by Hieronymus, Clemens, John Chrysostomos, and Hugo of S. Victor. Römer ascribes these works to the influence of provost Gerhard (1178-1205) (Römer, 335).
